04482nam a22005175i 9780773568778DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735687787 a10.1515/97807735687782doi  a(DE-B1597)655674  a(OCoLC)697733002  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aKE7709bC626 2000eb 7aLAW0000002bisacsh04a323.1/197307151 aCoates, Ken, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMarshall Decision and Native Rights :bThe Marshall Decision and Mi'kmaq Rights in the Maritimes /cKen Coates. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (432 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v2500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tOf Eels, Judges, and Lobsters: The Marshall Challenge and the Supreme Court Decision -- tPaying the Price for History: Mi’kmaq, Maliseet, and Colonists from Treaties to Irrelevance -- tMi’kmaq and Maliseet Frustrations: Social Crises and Government Responses -- tPrelude to Marshall: Aboriginal and Treaty Rights in Canada -- tThomas Peter Paul and the Mi’kmaq Logging Dispute -- tThe Marshall Crisis and East Coast Confrontations -- tPostlude to Marshall: Joshua Bernard, Lobster Licences, and the Refinement of Mi’kmaq Rights -- tWhat Does It Mean? The Marshall Decision, East Coast Fisheries, and Aboriginal Rights -- tAppendices -- tMaritime First Nations Communities: Population -- tLobster Quotas and Mi’kmaq Fishing Rights -- tTreaty of 1760 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Marshall Decision and Native Rights Ken Coates explains the cross-cultural, legal, and political implications of the recent Supreme Court decision on the Donald Marshall case. He describes the events, personalities, and conflicts that brought the Maritimes to the brink of a major confrontation between Mi'kmaq and the non-Mi'kmaq fishers in the fall of 1999, detailing the bungling by federal departments and the lack of police preparedness. He shows how political, business, and Mi'kmaq leaders in the Maritimes handled the volatile situation, urging non-violence and speaking out against racism, in contrast to the way federal and regional leaders have responded in other parts of the country. Legal victories such as Marshall, argues Coates, are a double-edged sword that provide greater legal clarity but expand the gap between indigenous and non-indigenous peoples in Canada. Coates recounts the history of Mi'kmaq-white contact in the region and considers the impact of native rights on natural resources, showing that the costs will be borne mainly by rural Canadians. By placing the local and regional reaction to the Marshall decision in the broader historical, national, and international context of indigenous political and legal rights The Marshall Decision and Native Rights shows how little Canada has learned from three decades of First Nations legal conflicts and how far the country is from meaningful reconciliation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356877840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773568778423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773568778/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles